Not fewer than 50 people were killed in a stampede, as crowd of mourners packed the streets for the funeral rites of a slain military Iranian military commander in his hometown of Kerman yesterday, forcing the burial to be postponed. Tens of thousands of people had gathered in Kerman to pay tribute to General Qassem Soleimani, who was killed in a US drone strike in Iraq on Friday. Stampede however ensued  amid the crush, killing 32 people and injuring about 190, the semi-official Fars news agency reported, citing an emergency services official.  35 reported dead, while others reported fatalities without giving figures. Iran’s ISNA news agency said the burial of Soleimani had been postponed, but did not say how long the delay would last. “Today because of the heavy congestion of the crowd unfortunately a number of our fellow citizens who were mourning were injured and a number were killed,” emergency medical services chief Pirhossein Kolivand told reporters. However a senior Iranian official said Tehran was considering 13 scenarios to avenge his killing. In Washington, the US defense secretary denied reports that the US military was preparing to withdraw from Iraq, where Tehran has vied with Washington for influence over nearly two decades of war and unrest. Soleimani was responsible for building up Tehran’s network of proxy armies across the Middle East and he was a key figure in orchestrating Iran’s long-standing campaign to drive US forces out of its neighbor Iraq. US and Iranian warnings of new strikes and retaliation have also stoked concerns about a broader Middle East conflict and led to calls in the US Congress for legislation to stop US President Donald Trump going to war with Iran. “We will take revenge, a hard and definitive revenge,” the head of Iran’s Revolutionary Guards, General Hossein Salami, told the crowds in Kerman prior to the stampede.